"Travers M.-A.S., Basuyaux O., Le Goïc N., Huchette S., Nicolas J.-L., Koken M., Paillard C.","Influence of temperature and spawning effort on Haliotis tuberculata mortalities caused by Vibrio harveyi: An example of emerging vibriosis linked to global warming",2009,"Global Change Biology","15","6",,"1365","1376",,,10.1111/j.1365-2486.2008.01764.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-65549171504&partnerID=40&md5=66349851f3b217faf620123ff1cde617","France Haliotis, Kerazan, Lilia, 29880 Plouguerneau, France; Laboratoire des Sciences de l'Environnement MARin, Institut Universitaire Européen de la Mer, Université de Bretagne Occidentale, 29280 Plouzané, France; Syndicat Mixte Pour l'Equipement du Littoral (SMEL), Zac de Blainville, 50560 Blainville-sur-Mer, France; Laboratoire de Physiologie des Invertébrés, Institut Francais de Recherche Pour l'Exploitation de la Mer (IFREMER), 29280 Plouzané, France","Travers, M.-A.S., France Haliotis, Kerazan, Lilia, 29880 Plouguerneau, France, Laboratoire des Sciences de l'Environnement MARin, Institut Universitaire Européen de la Mer, Université de Bretagne Occidentale, 29280 Plouzané, France; Basuyaux, O., Syndicat Mixte Pour l'Equipement du Littoral (SMEL), Zac de Blainville, 50560 Blainville-sur-Mer, France; Le Goïc, N., Laboratoire des Sciences de l'Environnement MARin, Institut Universitaire Européen de la Mer, Université de Bretagne Occidentale, 29280 Plouzané, France; Huchette, S., France Haliotis, Kerazan, Lilia, 29880 Plouguerneau, France; Nicolas, J.-L., Laboratoire de Physiologie des Invertébrés, Institut Francais de Recherche Pour l'Exploitation de la Mer (IFREMER), 29280 Plouzané, France; Koken, M., Laboratoire des Sciences de l'Environnement MARin, Institut Universitaire Européen de la Mer, Université de Bretagne Occidentale, 29280 Plouzané, France; Paillard, C., Laboratoire des Sciences de l'Environnement MARin, Institut Universitaire Européen de la Mer, Université de Bretagne Occidentale, 29280 Plouzané, France","Since 1998, Haliotis tuberculata mass mortalities have been occurring regularly in wild abalone populations in France during their reproductive period and in conjunction with seawater summer temperature maxima and Vibrio harveyi presence. To confirm the importance of bacterial exposure, temperature and reproductive status on abalone susceptibility, experimental infections via bath exposure were performed using abalone ranging from immature to reproductively mature. Ripe abalone were more susceptible to the bacterium than immature specimens (P<0.001), and a difference of only 1°C in temperature had a highly significant impact on the mortalities (P<0.001). The natural mortalities that were surveyed during summer 2007 confirmed that recent epidemic losses of European abalone appeared in conjunction with host reproductive stress, elevated temperatures and presence of the pathogen V. harveyi. In view of the elevation of the mean summer temperatures observed in Brittany and Normandy over the last 25 years, this temperature-dependent vibriosis represents a new case of emerging disease associated with global warming. © 2009 Blackwell Publishing.","Abalone; Disease; Field; Reproduction","bacterium; epidemic; experimental study; gastropod; global warming; mortality; reproductive status; snail; spawning; temperature effect; Eurasia; Europe; France; Western Europe; Bacteria (microorganisms); Haliotidae; Haliotis tuberculata; Vibrio harveyi",,,,,,"Aguirre-Guzman, G., Ruiz, H., Ascencio, F., A review of extracellular virulence product of Vibrio species important in diseases of cultivated shrimp (2004) Aquaculture Research, 35, pp. 1395-1404; Altstatt, J.M., Ambrose, R.F., Engle, J.M., Haaker, P.L., Lafferty, K.D., Raimondi, P.T., Recent declines of black abalone Haliotis cracherodi in the mainland coast of central California (1996) Marine Ecology Progress Series, 142, pp. 185-192; Austin, B., Zhang, X.H., Vibrio harveyi: A significant pathogen of marine vertebrates an